message.content:
The start symbol S has only two productions:

1. S → NT22 NT19  
2. S → NT13 NT21  

Examine the first alternative:  

NT22 can produce only the two–token sequences  
• (t7 | t2) t0  (via NT22 → NT5 NT16)  
• t4 (t4 | t1 | t7) (via NT22 → NT1 NT27)

In every case the very first symbol generated by NT22 is t7, t2 or t4 – never t5.  
Since the string to be recognised begins with t5, the derivation
S → NT22 NT19 is impossible.

Thus any successful derivation must use

S → NT13 NT21

NT21 is either
• the single terminal t3 (NT21 → 't3'), or
• a string produced by NT17 NT17 (minimum length 4 and always contains at least one t0, because NT17 → NT21 NT8 and NT8 can only end with t0).

The given string ends with “… t4 t4 t4 t3”.  
A suffix of this form cannot be derived by NT17 NT17 (no t0 appears), so NT21 must be the single terminal t3 – i.e. it corresponds exactly to the last symbol of the input.  
Consequently the remaining first 21 symbols must be generated by NT13.

NT13, however, expands only as

• NT13 → 't3'                        (length 1)  
• NT13 → NT2 NT9                   (length ≥ 2)

Because 21 > 1, we require NT13 → NT2 NT9, so the 21-symbol prefix must be split into
a prefix derived from NT2 and a suffix derived from NT9.

But NT2 can start with t5 only in its terminal production NT2 → 't5', whose length is exactly 1.  
Therefore the split is forced:

position 1      positions 2…21  
t5              t3 t5 t4 t6 t5 t8 t0 t2 t4 t4 t8 t1 t4 t8 t8 t7 t6 t4 t4 t4  
NT2             NT9

We are left with the task of generating the 20-symbol tail by NT9.  
NT9 has only two productions:

1. NT9 → NT4 NT20  
2. NT9 → NT33 NT20

Thus the 20-symbol block must be divisible into some left part that derives NT4 or NT33 and a right part that derives NT20.

The possibilities for NT20 are very limited:

• NT20 → 't1'                        (single symbol t1)  
• NT20 → NT31 NT31             (two consecutive t8 t8)  
• NT20 → NT0 NT32              (length ≥ 3, and necessarily ends in t6, because every derivation of NT32 ends with the terminal t6)

Looking at the 20-symbol block

t3 t5 t4 t6 t5 t8 t0 t2 t4 t4 t8 t1 t4 t8 t8 t7 t6 t4 t4 t4

the only candidate substrings that match any of the fixed terminal patterns of NT20 are:

• a single t1 (the 12ᵗʰ symbol),  
• the pair t8 t8 (symbols 14–15), and  
• the suffix … t6 (symbol 17) followed by three t4’s (symbols 18–20) – which cannot happen because every derivation of NT0 NT32 would put the required t6 at the very end, not in the middle.

Choosing t1 or t8 t8 for NT20 leaves either 8 or 6 trailing symbols that would have to be absorbed by NT20 (impossible) or ignored (also impossible), because NT4 and NT33 can only cover the prefix, not symbols after NT20. 

Therefore no division of the 20-symbol block satisfies NT9 → (NT4 | NT33) NT20, so the block cannot be generated by NT9 at all.

Since the 21-symbol prefix cannot derive NT13, the whole string cannot derive S.

Hence the grammar does not generate the given string.

No

The first symbol of any sentence generated by the grammar must be produced by the left-most child of the start symbol S.

S has only two productions
  S → NT22 NT19
  S → NT13 NT21
so the first token of every derivation is generated inside NT22 or inside NT13.

1.  NT22 can begin with NT5 (from NT22 → NT5 NT16) or with NT1 (from NT22 → NT1 NT27).   
    NT5 can generate either the terminal t7 or t2 (or a longer phrase that still starts with t7 or t2);  
    NT1 can generate only the terminal t4.  
    Hence every sentence that starts through NT22 must begin with t7, t2 or t4.

2.  NT13 can begin with the terminal t3 (via NT13 → 't3') or with whatever NT2 starts with (via NT13 → NT2 NT9).   
    NT2, however, can start only with t3, t5, t4 or t7 (it derives
    NT27, NT30 or NT34 on its left–hand side, all of which start with one of these four terminals).  
    Therefore every sentence that starts through NT13 must begin with t3, t5, t4 or t7.

Consequently, every string generated by S must start with one of the terminals
   t2, t3, t4, t5 or t7.

The string we are asked to recognise begins with the terminal t0:

   t0  t7  t5  t5  …

Since t0 is not among the possible initial symbols listed above, no derivation from S can produce this string.  Therefore the given string is **not** in the language of the grammar.

No

The start symbol S can only expand in two ways:

1. S → NT22 NT19  
   – First token comes from NT22.  
   – NT22 can expand to NT5 NT16 or NT1 NT27.  
     • NT1 gives the terminal t4.  
     • NT16 gives the terminal t0.  
     • NT5 begins with either t7 / t2 (directly) or with NT27 (which in turn begins with t4 / t1 / t7 or, via its binary rules, with t2 or t4).  
   – Consequently every string produced by NT22 must begin with one of  
     {t4, t0, t7, t2, t1}.  
     It can never begin with t8.

2. S → NT13 NT21  
   – First token comes from NT13.  
   – NT13 expands to the terminal t3 or to NT2 NT9.  
     • NT2 begins with t3 or t5, or with NT34 / NT27 / NT30, all of which ultimately start with t3, t4, t5, t6, t7, or t2 (never t8).  
   – Therefore every string generated via this branch must start with  
     {t3, t4, t5, t6, t7, t2}.  
     It can never begin with t8.

In both possible derivations from S, the very first symbol of any generated string cannot be t8.  
The given string starts with t8.

Hence the string cannot be generated by this grammar.

No

In a Chomsky-normal-form tree, every pair of adjacent terminals must be produced by a parent node whose two children each derive exactly one of those terminals.  
Consequently, for any adjacent pair of terminals σ₁ σ₂ in the string there must be a binary rule A → B C such that B ⇒* σ₁ and C ⇒* σ₂.

In the given grammar the only non-terminals that can yield the terminals  

 t8 are NT10 and NT31  
 t1 are NT27 and NT20  

Therefore, to obtain the adjacent pair “t8 t1” the grammar would need a binary rule whose left child is NT10 or NT31 and whose right child is NT27 or NT20.

Examining every binary production in the grammar, the only rules that have NT10 or NT31 on the left side of the right-hand pair are  

 NT26 → NT10 NT31  
 NT20 → NT31 NT31  

In both rules the right child is NT31, never NT27 or NT20.  
Hence no rule can place a symbol that derives t1 immediately to the right of a symbol that derives t8, making the adjacency “t8 t1” impossible in any generated sentence.

The supplied string contains “t8 t1” twice (at positions 10-11 and 19-20). Because that adjacent pair cannot be produced by the grammar, the whole string cannot be generated.

No

The start symbol S can expand in only two ways:

1. S → NT22 NT19  
   • NT22 is always exactly two terminals (either “t7 t0”, “t2 t0”, “t4 t4”, “t4 t1” or “t4 t7”).  
   • NT19, if it is a single terminal, is “t5” or “t0”; otherwise its multi-terminal forms all end in “t4” (coming from NT1 or NT30).  
   Hence the last symbol produced by NT19 is never “t5” unless NT19 itself is just “t5”, in which case the whole string would be 3 (=2+1) symbols long – far shorter than the required 34.  
   So the string cannot be derived through S → NT22 NT19.

2. S → NT13 NT21  
   • NT21 is either the single terminal “t3” or something built from NT17. Every occurrence of “t0”, “t2”, “t3”, “t7” or “t8” that NT21 can create ultimately comes from NT8, whose only terminal is “t0”.  
   • Thus every terminal appearing in any word generated by NT21 is among {t0, t3, t7, t8, t2}.  The terminal “t5” can never be produced by NT21.  
   Because the given string ends with “t5”, it cannot be produced by NT21, and therefore it cannot be produced via S → NT13 NT21.

Since neither of the only two possible top-level derivations can yield the required 34-symbol string ending in “… t4 t5”, the grammar does not generate the provided string.
